  "prompt": "When do the rabies symptoms occur in humans?",
  "response": "Rabies symptoms in humans typically appear once the virus has made its way to the central nervous system. This incubation period can vary widely, generally from 1 to 3 months, although cases have been known where symptoms appear as early as a week or as late as several years after exposure.\n\nThe initial symptoms often resemble those of the flu, including fever, headache, and general weakness or discomfort. As the disease progresses, more severe neurological symptoms emerge, such as:\n\n- Anxiety and confusion\n- Agitation and hyperactivity\n- Difficulty swallowing, leading to hydrophobia (fear of water)\n- Excessive salivation\n- Hallucinations\n- Partial paralysis\n\nOnce these acute symptoms begin, rabies is nearly always fatal. Therefore, if someone has been bitten or scratched by an animal that might be rabid, it's crucial to seek medical attention immediately for post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) treatment, which is highly effective if administered promptly.",
